The paper focuses on analyzing social influence in human behavior, which falls under the category of social computing (cs.SOC) and social network analysis (cs.SI). The use of community-based features and supervised learning algorithms also suggests a connection to artificial intelligence (cs.AI) and machine learning (cs.LG). Additionally, the paper discusses the role of physical location and homophily, which could be related to cybersecurity (cs.CYBER) and privacy concerns in social networks.
